National Hockey League - Expected Draft Pick Values using Goals Above Replacement and Python

# We start off by importing the necessary libraries


import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import os
import re
import numpy as np
import openpyxl

Hockey has always been my favourite sport, and one of the reasons I decided to learn Python was to do sports analytics. I've always enjoyed the NHL draft. I feel like it's one of the very few places left where teams can get an actual competitive edge over other teams, and that there are still lots of inefficiencies that can be exploited. I started by gathering data from the 2007-2016 NHL drafts and putting them all in 1 master list. The reason I choose this date range is because 2007 is the start of the NHL's advanced analytics era, with the NHL making more and more data publicly available. I picked 2016 as an end date because players are drafted at 18 years old. 2016 drafted players are in their prime years now. Picks from recent draft years, say 2023 and 2024, have yet to make a significant impact in the NHL: it would be misleading to include them in this analysis.

def read_data_from_excel(filename):
    all_years_dfs = {}
    combined_df_draft = pd.DataFrame()

    with pd.ExcelFile(filename, engine='openpyxl') as xls:
        for sheet_name in xls.sheet_names:
            df = pd.read_excel(xls, sheet_name)
            all_years_dfs[sheet_name] = df
            combined_df_draft = pd.concat([combined_df_draft, df], ignore_index=True)

    return all_years_dfs, combined_df_draft

filename = "nhl_draft_picks.xlsx"
all_years_dfs, combined_df_draft = read_data_from_excel(filename)

To estimate a player's value, I have decided to use Goals Above Replacement.While not perfect (no stat is!), it is a good estimate for a player's value during his career. You can read the full methodology for WAR/GAR here: https://evolving-hockey.com/blog/wins-above-replacement-history-philosophy-and-objectives-part-1/

Essentially, it tries to measure a player's impact over that of a "replacement" level player, meaning a player that can be signed at any time for league minimum salary, and is expected to play a very limited amount of minutes in a game.

def merge_csv_files(folder):
    all_files_dfs = {}
    combined_df_gar = pd.DataFrame()

    for file in os.listdir(folder):
        if file.endswith(".csv"):
            file_path = os.path.join(folder, file)
            year = file[3:7]  # Extract the year from the file name (e.g., '2007' from 'GAR2007.csv')
            df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
            all_files_dfs[year] = df
            combined_df_gar = pd.concat([combined_df_gar, df], ignore_index=True)  # Fixed append issue

    return all_files_dfs, combined_df_gar

Now we get to the interesting part: the results. The intuition that earlier picks are worth more looks accurate. A few players have negative value: that means that they have performed worse than a replacement-level player. There's a lot of players at or around 0 GAR, especially in the later rounds.This is normal as most players drafted never even make it to the NHL, it is quite hard to break through in the most competitive and skilled league in the world.

I used a simple generalized additive model (GAM) to smoothen the curve and get estimates for the value of each pick at a specific draft slot.

In [12]:
from pygam import LinearGAM, s


# Remove rows with NaN values in 'overallPickNumber' and 'GAR' columns
clean_data = selected_columns_df.dropna(subset=['overallPickNumber', 'GAR'])

# Extract 'overallPickNumber' and 'GAR' as NumPy arrays
X = clean_data['overallPickNumber'].to_numpy()
y = clean_data['GAR'].to_numpy()


# Applying GAM

gam = LinearGAM(s(0)).fit(X, y)

unique_pick_numbers = np.unique(X)
predicted_gar_values = gam.predict(unique_pick_numbers)
In [13]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))

# Plot the GAM-predicted points
plt.scatter(unique_pick_numbers, predicted_gar_values, s=50, label='GAM-predicted GAR')

plt.title('Goals above Replacement vs Overall Pick Number (GAM Predictions)', fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Overall Pick Number', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('First 7 seasons GAR', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title='GAM Predictions', title_fontsize=14, fontsize=12)
plt.show()

The above graph is very interesting: it shows us that the first 10 or so picks (even more in the top 3) are very valuable, and the drop off is quick after, as the value creeps towards zero in later rounds. I thought this did a decent job for a first attempt, however I wanted to represent the fact that the first two picks are even more valuable than other first round picks. In recent years, we've seen superstars Connor Mcdavid, John tavares, Auston matthews and Sydney Crosby drafted at the top of the draft. These players were (and are still) considered some of the very best in the NHL.

In [14]:
first_pick_dummy = (X == 1).astype(int)
second_pick_dummy = (X == 2).astype(int)

X_augmented = np.column_stack((X, first_pick_dummy, second_pick_dummy))

gam_augmented = LinearGAM(s(0) + s(1) + s(2)).fit(X_augmented, y)


unique_first_pick_dummy = (unique_pick_numbers == 1).astype(int)
unique_second_pick_dummy = (unique_pick_numbers == 2).astype(int)

# Stack unique_pick_numbers and dummy variables
unique_pick_numbers_augmented = np.column_stack((unique_pick_numbers, unique_first_pick_dummy, unique_second_pick_dummy))

# Predict GAR values
predicted_gar_values_augmented = gam_augmented.predict(unique_pick_numbers_augmented)

This confirms our intuition that earlier picks are much more valuable. I also wanted to use this data to answer the following question: are teams overestimating the value of a players height and weight? NHL teams frequently go on and on about size (You can't teach size!!) and frequently draft them very high in the draft, sometimes despite their lack of high-end skills. Would teams be better off staying away from the taller players in favor of the shorter players? Let's find out!

The average player is somewhere around 6 FT (72 inches or 183cm) tall. I considered anyone above 6ft tall, and anyone below that short. I also used their weight to calculate BMI.

In [22]:
final_df = merged_df_with_predictions[['playerName', 'overallPickNumber', 'triCode', 'height', 'weight', 'Position', 'draftYear', 'GAR', 'predicted_GAR', 'GAR_diff', 'Hit_or_Miss']]
final_df['height_diff'] = final_df['height'] - 72
# Convert weight from pounds to kilograms
final_df['weight_kg'] = final_df['weight'] * 0.453592

# Convert height from inches to meters
final_df['height_m'] = final_df['height'] * 0.0254

# Calculate BMI
final_df['BMI'] = final_df['weight_kg'] / (final_df['height_m'] ** 2)
final_df['bmi_diff'] = final_df['BMI'] - 25


# Create weight bins:

final_df['weight_bins'] = pd.cut(final_df['weight'], bins=range(130, 260, 10), include_lowest=True)

The calgary flames were the best drafters over the 2007-2016 drafts. Other top drafters include Colorado, Tampa Bay, and Boston: all teams that have been very good over the past decade. The worst drafters were the Florida Panthers, Vancouver Canucks, and Buffalo Sbres. The edmonton oilers also underperformed their draft slot, given how much good draft picks they had available to them over the years.
